    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-02-07T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-02-07T19:00:00-05:00" n="516"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d516">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.939/263 Suppl.: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-02-07T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 7, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>55. Reference Department’s 50, February 6, 3 p.m., and your despatch No. 4421,
                    January 16,<note n="47" xml:id="d516fn47">Latter not printed.</note> in regard
                    to interference by the Japanese with linen shipments from Swatow.</p>
                <p>Your despatch under reference has just been received. The Department authorizes
                    you to amend the proposed <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> in order to take
                    cognizance of the Japanese reply of December 27 to your representations of
                    November 15<note n="48" xml:id="d516fn48">Neither printed.</note> and to express
                    dissent with the contention of the Japanese military authorities at Swatow that
                    the exactions of $500.00 per ton are voluntary donations.</p>
                <p>Please send to Shanghai for repetition to the Department by naval radio the text
                    of the <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> which you leave at the Japanese
                    Foreign Office.</p>
                <p>Sent to Tokyo via Peiping. Repeated to Shanghai and Swatow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
